# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: openpyxl-excel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] CSV is not limited to a particular character encoding but should be and is commonly used with UTF-8, particularly because it does not provide a way to indicate the character encoding.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] The CSV format predates personal computers by more than a decade.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] The IBM Fortran (level H extended) compiler under OS/360 supported list-directed ("free-form") input/output, with commas between values, in 1972.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] List-directed input/output was defined in FORTRAN 77, approved in 1978.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] List-directed input used commas or spaces for delimiters, so unquoted character strings could not contain commas or spaces.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] The term "comma-separated value" and the "CSV" abbreviation were in use by 1983.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] The manual for the Osborne Executive computer, which bundled the SuperCalc spreadsheet, documents the CSV quoting convention that allows strings to contain embedded commas.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Comma-separated value lists are easier to type (for example into punched cards) than fixed-column-aligned data, and they were less prone to producing incorrect results if a value was punched one column off from its intended location.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Comma separated files are used for the interchange of database information between machines of two different architectures.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] The plain-text character of CSV files largely avoids incompatibilities such as byte-order and word size.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] The files are largely human-readable, so it is easier to deal with them in the absence of perfect documentation or communication.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] The main standardization initiative—transforming "*de facto* fuzzy definition" into a more precise and *de jure* one—was in 2005, with RFC 4180, defining CSV as a MIME Content Type.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Later, in 2013, some of RFC 4180's deficiencies were tackled by a W3C recommendation.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] In 2014 IETF published RFC 7111 describing the application of URI fragments to CSV documents.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] RFC 7111 specifies how row, column, and cell ranges can be selected from a CSV document using position indexes.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] In 2015 W3C, in an attempt to enhance CSV with formal semantics, publicized the first *drafts of recommendations* for CSV metadata standards, which began as *recommendations* in December of the same year.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] CSV can be informally described as plain text data consisting of one record per line, where each line has the same sequence of fields separated by a comma.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] The format is more formally described in the 2005 technical standard RFC 4180 which codifies the CSV format and defines the MIME type `text/csv` for the handling of text-based fields.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] This example illustrates that a CSV cannot be parsed by naïvely splitting the data by line terminators into lines, and then each line by commas.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] In 2011, Open Knowledge Foundation (OKF) and various partners created a data protocols working group, which later evolved into the Frictionless Data initiative.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] One of the main formats they released was the Tabular Data Package.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Tabular Data package was heavily based on CSV, using it as the main data transport format and adding basic type and schema metadata.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] (CSV lacks any type information to distinguish the string `1` from the number 1.) The Frictionless Data Initiative has also provided a standard CSV Dialect Description Format for describing different dialects of CSV, for example specifying the field separator or quoting rules.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] In 2013, the W3C "CSV on the Web" working group began to specify technologies providing higher interoperability for web applications using CSV or similar formats.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] The working group completed its work in February 2016 and is officially closed in March 2016 with the release of a set of documents and W3C recommendations for modeling "Tabular Data", and enhancing CSV with metadata and semantics.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] While the well-formedness of CSV data can readily be checked, testing validity and canonical form is less well developed, relative to more precise data formats, such as XML and SQL, which offer richer types and rules-based validation.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] CSV is commonly used for data exchange and is widely supported by data-oriented applications.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] It is often used to move tabular data between programs that natively operate on incompatible data – often in formats that are proprietary or undocumented.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] A common scenario is moving data from a database to a spreadsheet which, in general, use completely different formats.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Most database systems can export as CSV and most spreadsheet programs can import CSV-formatted data, leveraging CSV as an intermediate format.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Every major ecommerce platform provides support for exporting data as a CSV file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Common data science tools such as Pandas include the option to export data to CSV for long-term storage.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Benefits of CSV for data storage include the simplicity of CSV makes parsing and creating CSV files easy to implement and fast compared to other data formats, human readability making editing or fixing data simpler, and high compressibility leading to smaller data files.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Alternatively, CSV does not support more complex data relations and makes no distinction between null and empty values, and in applications where these features are needed other formats are preferred.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] More than 200 local, regional, and national data portals, such as those of the UK government and the European Commission, use CSV files with standardized data catalogs.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Some applications use CSV as a data interchange format to enhance its interoperability, exporting and importing CSV.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] CSV is supported by almost all spreadsheets and database management systems.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Spreadsheets including Apple Numbers, LibreOffice Calc, and Apache OpenOffice Calc. support reading CSV files.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Microsoft Excel also supports a dialect of CSV with restrictions in comparison to other spreadsheet software (e.g., as of 2019 Excel still cannot export CSV files in the commonly used UTF-8 character encoding, and separator is not enforced to be the comma).
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] LibreOffice Calc CSV importer is actually a more generic delimited text importer, supporting multiple separators at the same time as well as field trimming.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Various relational databases support saving query results to a CSV file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] PostgreSQL provides the `COPY` command, which allows for both saving and loading data to and from a file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] `COPY (SELECT * FROM articles) TO '/home/wikipedia/file.csv' (FORMAT csv)` saves the content of a table `articles` to a file called `/home/wikipedia/file.csv`.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Some relational databases, when using standard SQL, offer *foreign-data wrapper* (FDW).
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] For example, PostgreSQL offers the `CREATE FOREIGN TABLE` and `CREATE EXTENSION file_fdw` commands to configure any variant of CSV.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Databases like Apache Hive offer the option to express CSV or .csv.gz as an internal table format.
[src:openpyxl-excel/comma-separated-values] Programs that work with CSV may have limits on the maximum number of rows CSV files can have.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A **file format** is the way that information is encoded for storage in a computer file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] It may describe the encoding at various levels of abstraction including low-level bit and byte layout as well high-level organization such as markup and tabular structure.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A file format may be standardized (which can be proprietary or open) or it can be an *ad hoc* convention.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Some file formats are designed for very particular types of data: PNG files, for example, store bitmapped images using lossless data compression.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Other file formats, however, are designed for storage of several different types of data: the Ogg format can act as a container for different types of multimedia including any combination of audio and video, with or without text (such as subtitles), and metadata.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A text file can contain any stream of characters, including possible control characters, and is encoded in one of various character encoding schemes.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Some file formats, such as HTML, scalable vector graphics, and the source code of computer software are text files with defined syntaxes that allow them to be used for specific purposes.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Some file formats have a published specification describing the format and possibly how to verify the correctness of data in that format.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Such a document is not available for every format (sometimes because the format is considered a trade secret, and sometimes because a document was not authored).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Sometimes, a format is defined *de facto* by the behavior of the program that accesses the file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] If there is no specification available, a developer might reverse engineer the format by inspecting files in that format or acquire the specification for a fee and by signing a non-disclosure agreement.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Due to the time and money cost of these approaches, file formats with publicly available specifications tend to be supported by more programs.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Patent law (rather than copyright) can be used to protect the intellectual property inherent in a file format.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Although a patent for a file format is not directly permitted under US law, some formats encode data using a patented algorithm.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For example, prior to 2004, using compression with the GIF file format required the use of a patented algorithm, and though the patent owner did not initially enforce their patent, they later began collecting royalty fees.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] This has resulted in a significant decrease in the use of GIFs, and is partly responsible for the development of the alternative PNG format.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] However, the GIF patent expired in the US in mid-2003, and worldwide in mid-2004.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Both users and applications need to identify a file's format so that the file can be used appropriately.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Generally, the methods for identification vary by operating system, with each approach having its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] One popular method used by many operating systems, including Windows, macOS, CP/M, MS-DOS, VMS, and VM/CMS, is to indicate the format of a file with a suffix of the file name, known as the extension.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For example, an HTML document is identified by a file name that ends with .html or .htm, and a GIF image by .gif.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] In the now-antiquated FAT file system, file names were limited to eight characters for the base name plus a three-character extension, known as an 8.3 filename.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Due to the prevalence of this naming scheme, many formats still use three-character extensions even though modern systems support longer extensions.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Since there is no standardized list of extensions, more than one format can use the same extension – especially for three-letter extensions since there is a limited number of three-letter combinations.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] This situation can confuse both users and applications.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] One implication of indicating the file type with the extension is that the users and applications can be tricked into treating a file as a different format simply by renaming it.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For example, an HTML file can be treated as plain text by adding (or changing the existing) extension filename.txt.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Although this strategy is useful, it can be confusing to less technical users who accidentally make a file unusable (or "lose" it).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] To try to avoid this scenario, Windows and macOS support hiding the extension.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Hiding the extension, however, can create the appearance of multiple files with the same name in the same folder, which is confusing for people.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For example, an image may be needed both in .eps format (for publishing) and .png format (for web sites) and one might name them with the same base name (for example, CompanyLogo.eps and CompanyLogo.png).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] With extensions hidden they appear to have the same name: CompanyLogo.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Hiding extensions can also pose a security risk.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For example, a malicious user could create an executable program with an innocent name such as "Holiday photo.jpg.exe".
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The ".exe" would be hidden and an unsuspecting user would see "Holiday photo.jpg", which would appear to be a JPEG image, usually unable to harm the machine.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] However, the operating system would still see the ".exe" extension and run the program, which would then be able to cause harm to the computer.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The same is true with files with only one extension: as it is not shown to the user, no information about the file can be deduced without explicitly investigating the file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] To further trick users, it is possible to store an icon inside the program, in which case some operating systems' icon assignment for the executable file (.exe) would be overridden with an icon commonly used to represent JPEG images, making the program look like an image.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Extensions can also be spoofed: some Microsoft Word macro viruses create a Word file in template format and save it with a .doc extension.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Since Word generally ignores extensions and looks at the format of the file, these would open as templates, execute, and spread the virus.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] This represents a practical problem for Windows systems where extension-hiding is turned on by default.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A file's format may be indicated inside the file itself – either as information intended for this purpose or as identifiable data within the format that can be used for identification even though that is not its intended purpose.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Often intentionally placed information is located at the beginning of a file since this is relatively easy to read from a file both by users and applications.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] When the information at the beginning of the file is a structure that contains other metadata, then the structure is often called a *file header*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] When the file starts with a relatively small datum that only indicates the format, then it is often called a *magic number*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The metadata contained in a file header are usually stored at the start of the file, but might be present in other areas too, often including the end, depending on the file format or the type of data contained.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Character-based (text) files usually have character-based headers, whereas binary formats usually have binary headers, although this is not a rule.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Text-based file headers usually take up more space, but being human-readable, they can easily be examined by using simple software such as a text editor or a hexadecimal editor.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] As well as indicating the file format, file headers may contain metadata about the file and its contents.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For example, most image files store information about image format, size, resolution and color space, and optionally authoring information such as who made the image, when and where it was made, what camera model and photographic settings were used (Exif), and so on.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Such metadata may be used by software reading or interpreting the file during the loading process and afterwards.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] File headers may be used by an operating system to quickly gather information about a file without loading it all into memory, but doing so uses more of a computer's resources than reading directly from the directory information.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For instance, when a graphic file manager has to display the contents of a folder, it must read the headers of many files before it can display the appropriate icons, but these will be located in different places on the storage medium thus taking longer to access.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A folder containing many files with complex metadata such as thumbnail information may require considerable time before it can be displayed.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] If a header is binary hard-coded such that the header itself needs complex interpretation in order to be recognized, especially for metadata content protection's sake, there is a risk that the file format can be misinterpreted.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] It may even have been badly written at the source.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] This can result in corrupt metadata which, in extremely bad cases, might even render the file unreadable.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A more complex example of file headers are those used for wrapper (or container) file formats.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] One way to incorporate file type metadata is to store a "magic number" inside the file itself.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Originally, this term was used for 2-byte identifiers at the start of files, but since any binary sequence can be regarded as a number, any feature of a file format which uniquely distinguishes it can be used for identification.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] GIF images, for instance, always begin with the ASCII representation of either `GIF87a` or `GIF89a`, depending upon the standard to which they adhere.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Many file types, especially plain-text files, are harder to spot by this method.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] HTML files, for example, might begin with the string `<html>` (which is not case sensitive), or an appropriate document type definition that starts with `<!DOCTYPE html`, or, for XHTML, the XML identifier, which begins with `<?xml`.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The files can also begin with HTML comments, random text, or several empty lines, but still be usable HTML.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The magic number approach offers better guarantees that the format will be identified correctly, and can often determine more precise information about the file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Also, data must be read from the file itself, increasing latency as opposed to metadata stored in the directory.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Where file types do not lend themselves to recognition in this way, the system must fall back to metadata.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] On the other hand, a valid magic number does not guarantee that the file is not corrupt or is of a correct type.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] So-called shebang lines in script files are a special case of magic numbers.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] There, the magic number consists of human-readable text within the file that identifies a specific interpreter and options to be passed to it.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] This system was then enhanced with the Amiga standard Datatype recognition system.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Another method was the FourCC method, originating in OSType on Macintosh, later adapted by Interchange File Format (IFF) and derivatives.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A final way of storing the format of a file is to explicitly store information about the format in the file system, rather than within the file itself.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] This approach keeps the metadata separate from both the main data and the name, but is also less portable than either filename extensions or "magic numbers", since the format has to be converted from filesystem to filesystem.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] While this is also true to an extent with filename extensions— for instance, for compatibility with MS-DOS's three character limit— most forms of storage have a roughly equivalent definition of a file's data and name, but may have varying or no representation of further metadata.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Note that zip files and other archive files solve the problem of handling metadata.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A utility program collects multiple files together along with metadata about each file and the folders/directories they came from all within one new file (e.g. a zip file with extension .zip).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The new file is also compressed and possibly encrypted, but now is transmissible as a single file across operating systems by FTP transmissions or sent by email as an attachment.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] At the destination, the single file received has to be unzipped by a compatible utility to be useful.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The problems of handling metadata are solved this way using zip files or archive files.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The Mac OS' Hierarchical File System and HFS+ file system, and the Apple File System, store codes for *creator* and *type* as part of the directory entry for each file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] These codes could be any 4-byte sequence but were often selected so that the ASCII representation formed a sequence of meaningful characters, such as an abbreviation of the application's name or the developer's initials.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For instance a HyperCard "stack" file has a *creator* of WILD (from Hypercard's previous name, "WildCard") and a *type* of STAK.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The BBEdit text editor has a creator code of `R*ch` referring to its original programmer, Rich Siegel.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The type code specifies the format of the file, while the creator code specifies the default program to open it with when double-clicked by the user.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For example, the user could have several text files all with the type code of TEXT, but each open in a different program, due to having differing creator codes.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] This feature was intended so that, for example, human-readable plain-text files could be opened in a general-purpose text editor, while programming or HTML code files would open in a specialized editor or IDE.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] However, this feature was often the source of user confusion, as which program would launch when the files were double-clicked was often unpredictable.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] RISC OS uses a similar system, consisting of a 12-bit number which can be looked up in a table of descriptions—e.g. the hexadecimal number `FF5` is "aliased" to PoScript, representing a PostScript file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A Uniform Type Identifier (UTI) is a method used in macOS for uniquely identifying "typed" classes of entities, such as file formats.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] It was developed by Apple as a replacement for OSType (type & creator codes).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The UTI is a Core Foundation string, which uses a reverse-DNS string.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Some common and standard types use a domain called public (e.g. public.png for a Portable Network Graphics image), while other domains can be used for third-party types (e.g. com.adobe.pdf for Portable Document Format).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] UTIs can be defined within a hierarchical structure, known as a conformance hierarchy.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Thus, public.png conforms to a supertype of public.image, which itself conforms to a supertype of public.data.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A UTI can exist in multiple hierarchies, which provides great flexibility.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] In IBM OS/VS through z/OS, the VSAM catalog (prior to ICF catalogs) and the VSAM Volume Record in the VSAM Volume Data Set (VVDS) (with ICF catalogs) identifies the type of VSAM dataset.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] In IBM OS/360 through z/OS, a format 1 or 7 Data Set Control Block (DSCB) in the Volume Table of Contents (VTOC) identifies the Dataset Organization (DSORG) of the dataset described by it.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The HPFS, FAT12, and FAT16 (but not FAT32) filesystems allow the storage of "extended attributes" with files.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] These comprise an arbitrary set of triplets with a name, a coded type for the value, and a value, where the names are unique and values can be up to 64 KB long.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] There are standardized meanings for certain types and names (under OS/2).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] One such is that the ".TYPE" extended attribute is used to determine the file type.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Its value comprises a list of one or more file types associated with the file, each of which is a string, such as "Plain Text" or "HTML document".
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The NTFS filesystem also allows storage of OS/2 extended attributes, as one of the file *forks*, but this feature is merely present to support the OS/2 subsystem (not present in XP), so the Win32 subsystem treats this information as an opaque block of data and does not use it.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Instead, it relies on other file forks to store meta-information in Win32-specific formats.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] OS/2 extended attributes can still be read and written by Win32 programs, but the data must be entirely parsed by applications.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] On Unix and Unix-like systems, the ext2, ext3, ext4, ReiserFS version 3, XFS, JFS, FFS, and HFS+ filesystems allow the storage of extended attributes with files.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] These include an arbitrary list of "name=value" strings, where the names are unique and a value can be accessed through its related name.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The PRONOM Persistent Unique Identifier (PUID) is an extensible scheme of persistent, unique, and unambiguous identifiers for file formats, which has been developed by The National Archives of the UK as part of its PRONOM technical registry service.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] PUIDs can be expressed as Uniform Resource Identifiers using the info:pronom/ namespace.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Although not yet widely used outside of the UK government and some digital preservation programs, the PUID scheme does provide greater granularity than most alternative schemes.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] MIME types are widely used in many Internet-related applications, and increasingly elsewhere, although their usage for on-disc type information is rare.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] These consist of a standardised system of identifiers (managed by IANA) consisting of a *type* and a *sub-type*, separated by a slash—for instance, text/html or image/gif.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] These were originally intended as a way of identifying what type of file was attached to an e-mail, independent of the source and target operating systems.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] MIME types identify files on BeOS, AmigaOS 4.0 and MorphOS, as well as store unique application signatures for application launching.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] In AmigaOS and MorphOS, the Mime type system works in parallel with Amiga specific Datatype system.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] There are problems with the MIME types though; several organizations and people have created their own MIME types without registering them properly with IANA, which makes the use of this standard awkward in some cases.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] File format identifiers are another, not widely used way to identify file formats according to their origin and their file category.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] It was created for the Description Explorer suite of software.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] It is composed of several digits of the form `NNNNNNNNN-XX-YYYYYYY`.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The first part indicates the organization origin/maintainer (this number represents a value in a company/standards organization database), and the 2 following digits categorize the type of file in hexadecimal.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The final part is composed of the usual filename extension of the file or the international standard number of the file, padded left with zeros.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For example, the PNG file specification has the FFID of `000000001-31-0015948` where `31` indicates an image file, `0015948` is the standard number and `000000001` indicates the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Another less popular way to identify the file format is to examine the file contents for distinguishable patterns among file types.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The contents of a file are a sequence of bytes and a byte has 256 unique permutations (0–255).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Thus, counting the occurrence of byte patterns that is often referred to as byte frequency distribution gives distinguishable patterns to identify file types.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] There are many content-based file type identification schemes that use a byte frequency distribution to build the representative models for file type and use any statistical and data mining techniques to identify file types.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] There are several types of ways to structure data in a file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The most usual ones are described below.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Earlier file formats used raw data formats that consisted of directly dumping the memory images of one or more structures into the file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Unless the memory images also have reserved spaces for future extensions, extending and improving this type of structured file is very difficult.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] It also creates files that might be specific to one platform or programming language (for example a structure containing a Pascal string is not recognized as such in C).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] On the other hand, developing tools for reading and writing these types of files is very simple.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The limitations of the unstructured formats led to the development of other types of file formats that could be easily extended and be backward compatible at the same time.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] In this kind of file structure, each piece of data is embedded in a container that somehow identifies the data.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The container's scope can be identified by start- and end-markers of some kind, by an explicit length field somewhere, or by fixed requirements of the file format's definition.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Throughout the 1970s, many programs used formats of this general kind.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] For example, word-processors such as troff, Script, and Scribe, and database export files such as CSV.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Electronic Arts and Commodore-Amiga also used this type of file format in 1985, with their IFF (Interchange File Format) file format.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] A container is sometimes called a *"chunk"*, although "chunk" may also imply that each piece is small, and/or that chunks do not contain other chunks; many formats do not impose those requirements.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The information that identifies a particular "chunk" may be called many different things, often terms including "field name", "identifier", "label", or "tag".
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The identifiers are often human-readable, and classify parts of the data: for example, as a "surname", "address", "rectangle", "font name", etc.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] These are not the same thing as identifiers in the sense of a database key or serial number (although an identifier may well identify its *associated data* as such a key).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] With this type of file structure, tools that do not know certain chunk identifiers simply skip those that they do not understand.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Depending on the actual meaning of the skipped data, this may or may not be useful (CSS explicitly defines such behavior).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] This concept has been used again and again by RIFF (Microsoft-IBM equivalent of IFF), PNG, JPEG storage, DER (Distinguished Encoding Rules) encoded streams and files (which were originally described in CCITT X.409:1984 and therefore predate IFF), and Structured Data Exchange Format (SDXF).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] This is another extensible format, that closely resembles a file system (OLE Documents are actual filesystems), where the file is composed of 'directory entries' that contain the location of the data within the file itself as well as its signatures (and in certain cases its type).
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Good examples of these types of file structures are disk images, executables, OLE documents TIFF, libraries.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Some file formats like ODT and DOCX, being PKZIP-based, are both chunked and carry a directory.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The structure of a directory-based file format lends itself to modifications more easily than unstructured or chunk-based formats.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] The nature of this type of format allows users to carefully construct files that causes reader software to do things the authors of the format never intended to happen.
[src:openpyxl-excel/file-format] Directory-based file formats also use values that point at other areas in the file but if some later data value points back at data that was read earlier, it can result in an infinite loop for any reader software that assumes the input file is valid and blindly follows the loop.
[src:openpyxl-excel/introduction] Charts are composed of at least one series of one or more data points.
[src:openpyxl-excel/introduction] Series themselves are comprised of references to cell ranges.
[src:openpyxl-excel/introduction] By default the top-left corner of a chart is anchored to cell E15 and the size is 15 x 7.5 cm (approximately 5 columns by 14 rows).
[src:openpyxl-excel/introduction] This can be changed by setting the *anchor*, *width* and *height* properties of the chart.
[src:openpyxl-excel/introduction] The actual size will depend on operating system and device.
[src:openpyxl-excel/introduction] Other anchors are possible; see `openpyxl.drawing.spreadsheet_drawing` for further information.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Microsoft Office 2010 provides read support for ECMA-376, full support for ISO/IEC 29500 Transitional, and read support for ISO/IEC 29500 Strict.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Microsoft Office 2013 and later fully support ISO/IEC 29500 Strict, but do not use it as the default file format because of backwards compatibility concerns.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] In 2000, Microsoft released an initial version of an XML-based format for Microsoft Excel, which was incorporated in Office XP.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] In 2002, a new file format for Microsoft Word followed.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The Excel and Word formats—known as the Microsoft Office XML formats—were later incorporated into the 2003 release of Microsoft Office.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Microsoft announced in November 2005 that it would co-sponsor standardization of the new version of their XML-based formats through Ecma International as "Office Open XML".
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The presentation was made to Ecma by Microsoft's Jean Paoli and Isabelle Valet-Harper.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Microsoft submitted initial material to Ecma International Technical Committee TC45, where it was standardized to become ECMA-376, approved in December 2006.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] This standard was then fast-tracked in the Joint Technical Committee 1 of ISO and IEC.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] After initially failing to pass, an amended version of the format received the necessary votes for approval as an ISO/IEC Standard as the result of a JTC 1 fast-tracking standardization process that concluded in April 2008.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The resulting four-part International Standard (designated ISO/IEC 29500:2008) was published in November 2008 and can be downloaded from the ITTF.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] A technically equivalent set of texts is published by Ecma as *ECMA-376 Office Open XML File Formats—2nd edition* (December 2008); they can be downloaded from their website.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The ISO/IEC standardization of Office Open XML was controversial and embittered, with much discussion both about the specification and about the standardization process.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The article further says that Microsoft was accused of co-opting the standardization process by leaning on countries to ensure that it got enough votes at the ISO/IEC for Office Open XML to pass, although it does not specify exactly who accused Microsoft.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Under the Ecma International code of conduct in patent matters, participating and approving member organizations of ECMA are required to make their patent rights available on a reasonable and non-discriminatory (RAND) basis.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Holders of patents which concern ISO/IEC International Standards may agree to a standardized license governing the terms under which such patents may be licensed, in accord with the ISO/IEC/ITU common patent policy.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Microsoft, the main contributor to the standard, provided a covenant not to sue for its patent licensing.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The covenant received a mixed reception, with some like the Groklaw blog criticizing it, and others such as Lawrence Rosen, (an attorney and lecturer at Stanford Law School), endorsing it.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] This is limited to applications which do not deviate from the ISO/IEC 29500:2008 or Ecma-376 standard and to parties that do not "file, maintain or voluntarily participate in a patent infringement lawsuit against a Microsoft implementation of such Covered Specification".
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The Open Specification Promise was included in documents submitted to ISO/IEC in support of the ECMA-376 fast-track submission.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Ecma International asserted that, "The OSP enables both open source and commercial software to implement [the specification]".
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The Office Open XML specification exists in several versions.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The ECMA standard is structured in five parts to meet the needs of different audiences.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Later versions of the ECMA-376 standard are aligned and technically equivalent to the corresponding ISO standard.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The ISO/IEC standard is structured into four parts: Parts 1, 2 and 3 are independent standards; for example, Part 2, specifying Open Packaging Conventions, is used by other file formats including XPS and Design Web Format.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Part 4 is to be read as a modification to Part 1, which it requires.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] A technically equivalent set of texts is also published by Ecma as ECMA-376 2nd edition (2008).
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The standard specifies two levels of document & application conformance, *strict* and *transitional,* for each of WordprocessingML, PresentationML and SpreadsheetML, and also specifies applications' descriptions of *base* and *full*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] A fix for this had been suggested to ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 34/WG 4, and was approved in June 2009 as a recommendation for the first revision to Office Open XML.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Applications capable of reading documents compliant to ECMA-376 Edition 1 would regard ISO/IEC 29500-4 Transitional documents containing ISO 8601 dates as corrupt.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Some older versions of Microsoft Word and Microsoft Office are able to read and write `.docx` files after installation of the free compatibility pack provided by Microsoft, although some items, such as equations, are converted into images that cannot be edited.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Starting with Microsoft Office 2007, the Office Open XML file formats have become the default file format of Microsoft Office.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] However, due to the changes introduced in the Office Open XML standard, Office 2007 is not wholly in compliance with ISO/IEC 29500:2008.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Office 2010 includes support for opening documents of the ISO/IEC 29500:2008-compliant version of Office Open XML, but it can only save documents conforming to the *transitional*, not the *strict*, schemas of the specification.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] Note that the intent of the ISO/IEC is to allow the removal of the transitional variant from the ISO/IEC 29500 standard.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] The Document Foundation, creators of LibreOffice and promoters of the OpenDocument format (ODF), has argued that OOXML is excessively complex and unnecessarily convoluted.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] According to the foundation, this discourages interoperability and contributes to user dependence on Microsoft software.
[src:openpyxl-excel/office-open-xml] In a comparative analysis, they reported that OOXML files were many times longer and more intricate than ODF files containing the same text, describing the additional verbosity and structural elements as a "maze" of tags and metadata that complicates non-Microsoft implementations.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A **spreadsheet** is a computer application for computation, organization, analysis and storage of data in tabular form.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheets were developed as computerized analogs of paper accounting worksheets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The program operates on data entered in cells of a table.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Each cell may contain either numeric or text data, or the results of formulas that automatically calculate and display a value based on the contents of other cells.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The term *spreadsheet* may also refer to one such electronic document.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In modern spreadsheet applications, several spreadsheets, often known as "**worksheets**" or simply "sheets", are gathered together to form a "**workbook**".
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A workbook is physically represented by a file containing all the data for the book, the sheets, and the cells with the sheets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Worksheets are normally represented by tabs that flip between pages, each one containing one of the sheets, although Numbers changes this model significantly.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Cells in a multi-sheet book add the sheet name to their reference, for instance, "Sheet 1!C10".
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Some systems extend this syntax to allow cell references to different workbooks.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheet users can adjust any stored value and observe the effects on calculated values.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This makes the spreadsheet useful for "what-if" analysis since many cases can be rapidly investigated without manual recalculation.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Modern spreadsheet software can have multiple interacting sheets and can display data either as text and numerals or in graphical form.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Besides performing basic arithmetic and mathematical functions, modern spreadsheets provide built-in functions for common financial accountancy and statistical operations.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Such calculations as net present value, standard deviation, or regression analysis can be applied to tabular data with a pre-programmed function in a formula.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheet programs also provide conditional expressions, functions to convert between text and numbers, and functions that operate on strings of text.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheets have replaced paper-based systems throughout the business world.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Although they were first developed for accounting or bookkeeping tasks, they now are used extensively in any context where tabular lists are built, sorted, and shared.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] LANPAR, introduced by Remy Landau and Rene Pardo in 1969, was the first electronic spreadsheet on mainframe and time sharing computers.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] VisiCalc (1979) was the first electronic spreadsheet on a microcomputer, and it helped turn the Apple II into a popular and widely used personal computer.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Lotus 1-2-3 was the leading spreadsheet when DOS was the dominant operating system.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Microsoft Excel now has the largest market share on the Windows and Macintosh platforms.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A spreadsheet program is a standard feature of an office productivity suite.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In 2006 Google launched a beta release spreadsheet web application, this is currently known as Google Sheets and one of the applications provided in Google Drive.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A spreadsheet consists of a table of *cells* arranged into rows and columns and referred to by the X and Y locations.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] X locations, the columns, are normally represented by letters, "A," "B," "C," etc., while rows are normally represented by numbers, 1, 2, 3, etc.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A single cell can be referred to by addressing its row and column, "C10".
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This electronic concept of cell references was first introduced in LANPAR and a variant used in VisiCalc and known as "A1 notation".
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Additionally, spreadsheets have the concept of a *range*, a group of cells, normally contiguous.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] For instance, one can refer to the first ten cells in the first column with the range "A1:A10".
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] LANPAR innovated forward referencing/natural order calculation which didn't re-appear until Lotus 123 and Microsoft's MultiPlan Version 2.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Users interact with sheets primarily through the cells.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A given cell can hold data by simply entering it in, or a formula, which is normally created by preceding the text with an equals sign.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Data might include the string of text `hello world`, the number `5` or the date `10-Sep-97`.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A formula would begin with the equals sign, `=5*3`, but this would normally be invisible because the display shows the *result* of the calculation, `15` in this case, not the formula itself.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This may lead to confusion in some cases.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The key feature of spreadsheets is the ability for a formula to refer to the contents of other cells, which may, in turn, be the result of a formula.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] To make such a formula, one replaces a number with a cell reference.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] For instance, the formula `=5*C10` would produce the result of multiplying the value in cell C10 by the number 5.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] If C10 holds the value `3` the result will be `15`.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] But C10 might also hold its formula referring to other cells, and so on.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The ability to chain formulas together is what gives a spreadsheet its power.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Many problems can be broken down into a series of individual mathematical steps, and these can be assigned to individual formulas in cells.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Some of these formulas can apply to ranges as well, like the `SUM` function that adds up all the numbers within a range.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheets share many principles and traits of databases, but spreadsheets and databases are not the same things.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A spreadsheet is essentially just one table, whereas a database is a collection of many tables with machine-readable semantic relationships.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] While it is true that a workbook that contains three sheets is indeed a file containing multiple tables that can interact with each other, it lacks the relational structure of a database.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheets and databases are interoperable—sheets can be imported into databases to become tables within them, and database queries can be exported into spreadsheets for further analysis.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A spreadsheet program is one of the main components of an office productivity suite, which usually also contains a word processor, a presentation program, and a database management system.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Programs within a suite use similar commands for similar functions.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Usually, sharing data between the components is easier than with a non-integrated collection of functionally equivalent programs.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This was particularly an advantage at a time when many personal computer systems used text-mode displays and commands instead of a graphical user interface.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Humans have organized data into tables, that is, grids of columns and rows, since ancient times.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The Babylonians used clay tablets to store data as far back as 1800 BCE.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Other examples can be found in book-keeping ledgers and astronomical records.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Since at least 1906 the term "spread sheet" has been used in accounting to mean a grid of columns and rows in a ledger.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Prior to the rise of computerized spreadsheets, "spread" also referred to a newspaper or magazine item (text or graphics) that covers two facing pages, extending across the centerfold and treating the two pages as one large page.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A batch "spreadsheet" is indistinguishable from a batch compiler with added input data, producing an output report, *i.e.*, a 4GL or conventional, non-interactive, batch computer program.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] However, this concept of an electronic spreadsheet was outlined in the 1961 paper "Budgeting Models and System Simulation" by Richard Mattessich.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The subsequent work by Mattessich (1964a, Chpt.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] 9, *Accounting and Analytical Methods*) and its companion volume, Mattessich (1964b, *Simulation of the Firm through a Budget Computer Program*) applied computerized spreadsheets to accounting and budgeting systems (on mainframe computers programmed in FORTRAN IV).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] These batch Spreadsheets dealt primarily with the addition or subtraction of entire columns or rows (of input variables), rather than individual *cells*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In 1962, this concept of the spreadsheet, called BCL for Business Computer Language, was implemented on an IBM 1130 and in 1963 was ported to an IBM 7040 by R.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Brian Walsh at Marquette University, Wisconsin.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Primitive timesharing was available on those machines.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In 1968 BCL was ported by Walsh to the IBM 360/67 timesharing machine at Washington State University.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It was used to assist in the teaching of finance to business students.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Students were able to take information prepared by the professor and manipulate it to represent it and show ratios etc.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In 1964, a book entitled *Business Computer Language* was written by Kimball, Stoffells and Walsh.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Both the book and program were copyrighted in 1966 and years later that copyright was renewed.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In the late 1960s, Xerox used BCL to develop a more sophisticated version for their timesharing system.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A key invention in the development of electronic spreadsheets was made by Rene K.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Pardo and Remy Landau, who filed in 1970 U.S. patent 4,398,249 on a spreadsheet automatic natural order calculation algorithm.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit upheld that decision in 1996.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The software was called LANPAR — LANguage for Programming Arrays at Random.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This was conceived and entirely developed in the summer of 1969, following Pardo and Landau's recent graduation from Harvard University.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Pardo and Landau developed and implemented the software in 1969.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] LANPAR was used by Bell Canada, AT&T, and the 18 operating telephone companies nationwide for their local and national budgeting operations.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Without forward referencing/natural order calculation, the user had to refresh the spreadsheet until the values in all cells remained unchanged.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Once the cell values stayed constant, the user was assured that there were no remaining uncalculated forward references within the spreadsheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In 1968, three former employees from the General Electric computer company headquartered in Phoenix, Arizona set out to start their own software development house.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Edwards found themselves doing a large number of calculations when making tables for the business plans that they were presenting to venture capitalists.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] They decided to save themselves a lot of effort and wrote a computer program that produced their tables for them.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This program, originally conceived as a simple utility for their personal use, would turn out to be the first software product offered by the company that would become known as Capex Corporation.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] "AutoPlan" ran on GE's Time-sharing service; afterward, a version that ran on IBM mainframes was introduced under the name *AutoTab*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] (National CSS offered a similar product, CSSTAB, which had a moderate timesharing user base by the early 1970s.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] AutoPlan/AutoTab was not a WYSIWYG interactive spreadsheet program, it was a simple scripting language for spreadsheets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The user defined the names and labels for the rows and columns, then the formulas that defined each row or column.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] GE Information Services, which operated the time-sharing service, also launched its own spreadsheet system, Financial Analysis Language (FAL), circa 1974.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It was later supplemented by an additional spreadsheet language, TABOL, which was developed by an independent author, Oliver Vellacott in the UK.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Both FAL and TABOL were integrated with GEIS's database system, DMS.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The IBM Financial Planning and Control System was developed in 1976, by Brian Ingham at IBM Canada.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It was implemented by IBM in at least 30 countries.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It ran on an IBM mainframe and was the first application for financial planning developed with APL that completely hid the programming language from the end-user.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Through IBM's VM operating system, it was among the first programs to auto-update each copy of the application as new versions were released.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Users could specify simple mathematical relationships between rows and between columns.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Compared to any contemporary alternatives, it could support very large spreadsheets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It loaded actual financial planning data drawn from the legacy batch system into each user's spreadsheet monthly.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It was designed to optimize the power of APL through object kernels, increasing program efficiency by as much as 50 fold over traditional programming approaches.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] An example of an early "industrial weight" spreadsheet was APLDOT, developed in 1976 at the United States Railway Association on an IBM 360/91, running at The Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory in Laurel, MD.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The application was used successfully for many years in developing such applications as financial and costing models for the US Congress and for Conrail.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] APLDOT was dubbed a "spreadsheet" because financial analysts and strategic planners used it to solve the same problems they addressed with paper spreadsheet pads.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The concept of spreadsheets became widely known due to VisiCalc, developed for the Apple II in 1979 by VisiCorp staff Dan Bricklin and Bob Frankston.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Significantly, it also turned the personal computer from a hobby for computer enthusiasts into a business tool.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Unaware of LANPAR at the time, *PC World* magazine called VisiCalc the first electronic spreadsheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Bricklin has spoken of watching his university professor create a table of calculation results on a blackboard.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] When the professor found an error, he had to tediously erase and rewrite several sequential entries in the table, triggering Bricklin to think that he could replicate the process on a computer, using the blackboard as the model to view results of underlying formulas.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] VisiCalc for the Apple II went on to become the first killer application, a program so compelling, people would buy a particular computer just to use it.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It was ported to other computers, including CP/M machines, Atari 8-bit computers, and the Commodore PET, but VisiCalc remains best known as an Apple II program.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] SuperCalc was a spreadsheet application published by Sorcim in 1980, and originally bundled (along with WordStar) as part of the CP/M software package included with the Osborne 1 portable computer.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It quickly became the de facto standard spreadsheet for CP/M.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The introduction of Lotus 1-2-3 in November 1982 accelerated the acceptance of the IBM Personal Computer.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It was written especially for IBM PC DOS and had improvements in speed and graphics compared to VisiCalc on the Apple II, this helped it grow in popularity.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Lotus 1-2-3 was the leading spreadsheet for several years.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Microsoft released the first version of Excel for the Apple Macintosh on September 30, 1985, and then ported it to Windows, with the first version being numbered 2.05 (to synchronize with the Macintosh version 2.2) and released in November 1987.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Microsoft's Windows 3.x platforms of the early 1990s made it possible for their Excel spreadsheet application to take market share from Lotus.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] By the time Lotus responded with usable Windows products, Microsoft had begun to assemble their Office suite.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] By 1995, Excel was the market leader, edging out Lotus 1-2-3, and in 2013, IBM discontinued Lotus 1-2-3 altogether.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In 2006 Google launched their beta release Google Sheets, a web based spreadsheet application that can be accessed by multiple users from any device type using a compatible web browser, it can be used online and offline (with or without internet connectivity).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Google Sheets originated from a web-based spreadsheet application XL2Web developed by 2Web Technologies, combined with DocVerse which enabled multiple-user online collaboration of Office documents.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In 2016 Collabora Online Calc was launched, notable in that the web based spreadsheet could be hosted and integrated into any environment without dependency on a 3rd party for authentication or maintenance.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Collabora Online runs LibreOffice kit at its core, which grew from StarOffice that was launched 41 years ago in 1985.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Several companies have attempted to break into the spreadsheet market with programs based on very different paradigms.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Lotus introduced what is likely the most successful example, Lotus Improv, which saw some commercial success, notably in the financial world where its powerful data mining capabilities remain well respected to this day.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheet 2000 attempted to dramatically simplify formula construction, but was generally not successful.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The main concepts are those of a grid of cells, called a sheet, with either raw data, called values, or formulas in the cells.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Formulas say how to mechanically compute new values from existing values.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Values are general numbers, but can also be pure text, dates, months, etc.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Extensions of these concepts include logical spreadsheets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Various tools for programming sheets, visualizing data, remotely connecting sheets, displaying cells' dependencies, etc. are commonly provided.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A **"cell"** can be thought of as a box for holding data.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A single cell is usually referenced by its column and row (C2 would represent the cell containing the value 30 in the example table below).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Usually rows, representing the dependent variables, are referenced in decimal notation starting from 1, while columns representing the independent variables use 26-adic bijective numeration using the letters A-Z as numerals.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Its physical size can usually be tailored to its content by dragging its height or width at box intersections (or for entire columns or rows by dragging the column- or row-headers).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] An array of cells is called a *sheet* or *worksheet*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It is analogous to an array of variables in a conventional computer program (although certain unchanging values, once entered, could be considered, by the same analogy, constants).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In most implementations, many worksheets may be located within a single spreadsheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A worksheet is simply a subset of the spreadsheet divided for the sake of clarity.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Functionally, the spreadsheet operates as a whole and all cells operate as global variables within the spreadsheet (each variable having 'read' access only except its containing cell).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A cell may contain a value or a formula, or it may simply be left empty.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] By convention, formulas usually begin with **=** sign.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A value can be entered from the computer keyboard by directly typing into the cell itself.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Alternatively, a value can be based on a formula (see below), which might perform a calculation, display the current date or time, or retrieve external data such as a stock quote or a database value.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A standard of spreadsheets since the 1980s, this optional feature eliminates the need to manually request the spreadsheet program to recalculate values (nowadays typically the default option unless specifically 'switched off' for large spreadsheets, usually to improve performance).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Some earlier spreadsheets required a manual request to recalculate since the recalculation of large or complex spreadsheets often reduced data entry speed.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Many modern spreadsheets still retain this option.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Recalculation generally requires that there are no circular dependencies in a spreadsheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A dependency graph is a graph that has a vertex for each object to be updated, and an edge connecting two objects whenever one of them needs to be updated earlier than the other.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Dependency graphs without circular dependencies form directed acyclic graphs, representations of partial orderings (in this case, across a spreadsheet) that can be relied upon to give a definite result.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This feature refers to updating a cell's contents periodically with a value from an external source—such as a cell in a "remote" spreadsheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] For shared, Web-based spreadsheets, it applies to "immediately" updating cells another user has updated.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] All dependent cells must be updated also.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Once entered, selected cells (or the entire spreadsheet) can optionally be "locked" to prevent accidental overwriting.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Typically this would apply to cells containing formulas but might apply to cells containing "constants" such as a kilogram/pounds conversion factor (2.20462262 to eight decimal places).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Even though individual cells are marked as locked, the spreadsheet data are not protected until the feature is activated in the file preferences.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A cell or range can optionally be defined to specify how the value is displayed.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The default display format is usually set by its initial content if not specifically previously set, so that for example "31/12/2007" or "31 Dec 2007" would default to the cell format of *date*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Similarly adding a % sign after a numeric value would tag the cell as a percentage cell format.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The cell contents are not changed by this format, only the displayed value.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Some cell formats such as "numeric" or "currency" can also specify the number of decimal places.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This can allow invalid operations (such as doing multiplication on a cell containing a date), resulting in illogical results without an appropriate warning.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Depending on the capability of the spreadsheet application, each cell (like its counterpart the "style" in a word processor) can be separately formatted using the attributes of either the content (point size, color, bold or italic) or the cell (border thickness, background shading, color).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] To aid the readability of a spreadsheet, cell formatting may be conditionally applied to data; for example, a negative number may be displayed in red.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A cell's formatting does not typically affect its content and depending on how cells are referenced or copied to other worksheets or applications, the formatting may not be carried with the content.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In most implementations, a cell, or group of cells in a column or row, can be "named" enabling the user to refer to those cells by a name rather than by a grid reference.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Names must be unique within the spreadsheet, but when using multiple sheets in a spreadsheet file, an identically named cell range on each sheet can be used if it is distinguished by adding the sheet name.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] One reason for this usage is for creating or running macros that repeat a command across many sheets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Another reason is that formulas with named variables are readily checked against the algebra they are intended to implement (they resemble Fortran expressions).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The use of named variables and named functions also makes the spreadsheet structure more transparent.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In place of a named cell, an alternative approach is to use a cell (or grid) reference.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Most cell references indicate another cell in the same sheet, but a cell reference can also refer to a cell in a different sheet within the same spreadsheet, or (depending on the implementation) to a cell in another spreadsheet entirely, or a value from a remote application.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A typical **cell reference** in "A1" style consists of one or two case-insensitive letters to identify the column (if there are up to 256 columns: A–Z and AA–IV) followed by a row number (e.g., in the range 1–65536).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Either part can be relative (it changes when the formula it is in is moved or copied), or absolute (indicated with $ in front of the part concerned of the cell reference).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The alternative "R1C1" reference style consists of the letter R, the row number, the letter C, and the column number; relative row or column numbers are indicated by enclosing the number in square brackets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Most current spreadsheets use the A1 style, some providing the R1C1 style as a compatibility option.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] When the computer calculates a formula in one cell to update the displayed value of that cell, cell reference(s) in that cell, naming some other cell(s), causes the computer to fetch the value of the named cell(s).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Some spreadsheet implementations in Excel allow cell references to another spreadsheet (not the currently open and active file) on the same computer or a local network.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It may also refer to a cell in another open and active spreadsheet on the same computer or network that is defined as shareable.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In a spreadsheet, references to cells automatically update when new rows or columns are inserted or deleted.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Care must be taken, however, when adding a row immediately before a set of column totals to ensure that the totals reflect the values of the additional rows—which they often do not.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A circular reference occurs when the formula in one cell refers—directly, or indirectly through a chain of cell references—to another cell that refers back to the first cell.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Many common errors cause circular references.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] However, some valid techniques use circular references.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] These techniques, after many spreadsheet recalculations, (usually) converge on the correct values for those cells.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Likewise, instead of using a named range of cells, a range reference can be used.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A reference to a range of cells typically takes the form (A1:A6), which specifies all the cells in column A from row 1 through row 6.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A formula such as "=SUM(A1:A6)" would add all the cells specified and put the result in the cell containing the formula itself.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In the earliest spreadsheets, cells were a simple two-dimensional grid.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Over time, the model has expanded to include a third dimension, and in some cases a series of named grids, called sheets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The most advanced examples allow inversion and rotation operations which can slice and project the data set in various ways.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A formula identifies the calculation needed to place the result in the cell it is contained within.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A cell containing a formula, therefore, has two display components; the formula itself and the resulting value.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The formula is normally only shown when the cell is selected by "clicking" the mouse over a particular cell; otherwise, it contains the result of the calculation.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] When a cell contains a formula, it often contains references to other cells.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Such a cell reference is a type of variable.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Its value is the value of the referenced cell or some derivation of it.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] If that cell in turn references other cells, the value depends on the values of those.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] References can be relative (e.g., `A1`, or `B1:B3`), absolute (e.g., `$A$1`, or `$B$1:$B$3`) or mixed row– or column-wise absolute/relative (e.g., `$A1` is column-wise absolute and `A$1` is row-wise absolute).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The available options for valid formulas depend on the particular spreadsheet implementation but, in general, most arithmetic operations and quite complex nested conditional operations can be performed by most of today's commercial spreadsheets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Modern implementations also offer functions to access custom-build functions, remote data, and applications.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A formula may contain a condition (or nested conditions)—with or without an actual calculation—and is sometimes used purely to identify and **highlight errors**.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In the example below, it is assumed the sum of a column of percentages (A1 through A6) is tested for validity and an explicit message put into the adjacent right-hand cell.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] =IF(AND(A1<>"",B1<>""),A1/B1,"") means that if both cells A1 and B1 are not <> empty "", then divide A1 by B1 and display, other do not display anything.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] =IF(AND(A1<>"",B1<>""),IF(B1<>0,A1/B1,"Division by zero"),"") means that if cells A1 and B1 are not empty, and B1 is not zero, then divide A1 by B1, if B1 is zero, then display "Division by zero", and do not display anything if either A1 and B1 are empty.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] =IF(OR(A1<>"",B1<>""),"Either A1 or B1 show text","") means to display the text if either cells A1 or B1 are not empty.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The best way to build up conditional statements is step by step composing followed by trial and error testing and refining code.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A spreadsheet does not have to contain any formulas at all, in which case it could be considered merely a collection of data arranged in rows and columns (a database) like a calendar, timetable, or simple list.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Because of its ease of use, formatting, and hyperlinking capabilities, many spreadsheets are used solely for this purpose.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheets usually contain several supplied functions, such as arithmetic operations (for example, summations, averages, and so forth), trigonometric functions, statistical functions, and so forth.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In addition there is often a provision for *user-defined functions*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In Microsoft Excel, these functions are defined using Visual Basic for Applications in the supplied Visual Basic editor, and such functions are automatically accessible on the worksheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Also, programs can be written that pull information from the worksheet, perform some calculations, and report the results back to the worksheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In the figure, the name *sq* is user-assigned, and the function *sq* is introduced using the *Visual Basic* editor supplied with Excel.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] *Name Manager* displays the spreadsheet definitions of named variables *x* & *y*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Functions themselves cannot write into the worksheet but simply return their evaluation.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] However, in Microsoft Excel, subroutines can write values or text found within the subroutine directly to the spreadsheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The figure shows the Visual Basic code for a subroutine that reads each member of the named column variable *x*, calculates its square, and writes this value into the corresponding element of named column variable *y*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The *y* column contains no formula because its values are calculated in the subroutine, not on the spreadsheet, and simply are written in.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Whenever a reference is made to a cell or group of cells that are not located within the current physical spreadsheet file, it is considered as accessing a "remote" spreadsheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The contents of the referenced cell may be accessed either on the first reference with a manual update or more recently in the case of web-based spreadsheets, as a near real-time value with a specified automatic refresh interval.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Many spreadsheet applications permit charts and graphs (e.g., histograms, pie charts) to be generated from specified groups of cells that are dynamically re-built as cell contents change.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The generated graphic component can either be embedded within the current sheet or added as a separate object.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] To create an Excel histogram, a formula based on the REPT function can be used.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, first Javelin Software and Lotus Improv appeared.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Unlike models in a conventional spreadsheet, they utilized models built on objects called variables, not on data in cells of a report.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] These multi-dimensional spreadsheets enabled viewing data and algorithms in various self-documenting ways, including simultaneous multiple synchronized views.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] For example, users of Javelin could move through the connections between variables on a diagram while seeing the logical roots and branches of each variable.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This is an example of what is perhaps its primary contribution of the earlier Javelin—the concept of traceability of a user's logic or model structure through its twelve views.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A complex model can be dissected and understood by others who had no role in its creation.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] In these programs, a time series, or any variable, was an object in itself, not a collection of cells that happen to appear in a row or column.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Variables could have many attributes, including complete awareness of their connections to all other variables, data references, and text and image notes.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Calculations were performed on these objects, as opposed to a range of cells, so adding two-time series automatically aligns them in calendar time, or in a user-defined time frame.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Data were independent of worksheets—variables, and therefore data, could not be destroyed by deleting a row, column, or entire worksheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] For instance, January's costs are subtracted from January's revenues, regardless of where or whether either appears in a worksheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This permits actions later used in pivot tables, except that flexible manipulation of report tables, was but one of many capabilities supported by variables.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Moreover, if costs were entered by week and revenues by month, the program could allocate or interpolate as appropriate.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This object design enabled variables and whole models to reference each other with user-defined variable names and to perform multidimensional analysis and massive, but easily editable consolidations.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheets that have a formula language based upon logical expressions, rather than arithmetic expressions are known as logical spreadsheets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Such spreadsheets can be used to reason deductively about their cell values.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Just as the early programming languages were designed to generate spreadsheet printouts, programming techniques themselves have evolved to process tables (also known as spreadsheets or matrices) of data more efficiently in the computer itself.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheets are a popular end-user development tool.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] EUD denotes activities or techniques in which people who are not professional developers create automated behavior and complex data objects without significant knowledge of a programming language.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Many people find it easier to perform calculations in spreadsheets than by writing the equivalent sequential program.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This is due to several traits of spreadsheets.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] A ***"spreadsheet program"*** is designed to perform general computation tasks using spatial relationships rather than time as the primary organizing principle.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] It is often convenient to think of a spreadsheet as a mathematical graph, where the nodes are spreadsheet cells, and the edges are references to other cells specified in formulas.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] This is often called the dependency graph of the spreadsheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] References between cells can take advantage of spatial concepts such as relative position and absolute position, as well as named locations, to make the spreadsheet formulas easier to understand and manage.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheets usually attempt to automatically update cells when the cells depend on change.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] The earliest spreadsheets used simple tactics like evaluating cells in a particular order, but modern spreadsheets calculate following a minimal recomputation order from the dependency graph.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Later spreadsheets also include a limited ability to propagate values in reverse, altering source values so that a particular answer is reached in a certain cell.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Since spreadsheet cell formulas are not generally invertible, though, this technique is of somewhat limited value.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Many of the concepts common to sequential programming models have analogs in the spreadsheet world.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] For example, the sequential model of the indexed loop is usually represented as a table of cells, with similar formulas (normally differing only in which cells they reference).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p01] Spreadsheets have evolved to use scripting programming languages like VBA as a tool for extensibility beyond what the spreadsheet language makes easy.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] While spreadsheets represented a major step forward in quantitative modeling, they have deficiencies.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] Their shortcomings include the perceived unfriendliness of alpha-numeric cell addresses.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] Despite the high error risks often associated with spreadsheet authorship and use, specific steps can be taken to significantly enhance control and reliability by structurally reducing the likelihood of error occurrence at their source.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] These drawbacks are mitigated by the use of named variables for cell designations, and employing variables in formulas rather than cell locations and cell-by-cell manipulations.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] Graphs can be used to show instantly how results are changed by changes in parameter values.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] The spreadsheet can be made invisible except for a transparent user interface that requests pertinent input from the user, displays results requested by the user, creates reports, and has built-in error traps to prompt correct input.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] Specifically, spreadsheets typically contain many copies of the same formula.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] When the formula is modified, the user has to change every cell containing that formula.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] In contrast, most computer languages allow a formula to appear only once in the code and achieve repetition using loops: making them much easier to implement and audit.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] While there are built-in and third-party tools for desktop spreadsheet applications that address some of these shortcomings, awareness, and use of these is generally low.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] Many professionals in the financial field "don't know" how their spreadsheets are audited; only 6% invest in a third-party solution.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] Spreadsheet risk is the risk associated with deriving a materially incorrect value from a spreadsheet application that will be utilized in making a related (usually numerically based) decision.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] Examples include the valuation of an asset, the determination of financial accounts, the calculation of medicinal doses, or the size of a load-bearing beam for structural engineering.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] The risk may arise from inputting erroneous or fraudulent data values, from mistakes (or incorrect changes) within the logic of the spreadsheet or the omission of relevant updates (e.g., out of date exchange rates).
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] Some single-instance errors have exceeded US$1 billion.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] Because spreadsheet risk is principally linked to the actions (or inaction) of individuals it is defined as a sub-category of operational risk.
[src:openpyxl-excel/spreadsheet-p02] Despite this, research carried out by ClusterSeven revealed that around half (48%) of c-level executives and senior managers at firms reporting annual revenues over £50m said there were either no usage controls at all or poorly applied manual processes over the use of spreadsheets at the firms.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] There is support for the popular lxml library which will be used if it is installed.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] This is particular useful when creating large files.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] or browse https://pypi.python.org/pypi/Pillow/, pick the latest version and head to the bottom of the page for Windows binaries.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] Sometimes you might want to work with the checkout of a particular version.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] This may be the case if bugs have been fixed but a release has not yet been made.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] There is no need to create a file on the filesystem to get started with openpyxl.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] A workbook is always created with at least one worksheet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] Unless you modify its value, you will always get the first worksheet by using this method.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] Sheets are given a name automatically when they are created.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] They are numbered in sequence (Sheet, Sheet1, Sheet2, …).
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] Only cells (including values, styles, hyperlinks and comments) and certain worksheet attributes (including dimensions, format and properties) are copied.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] All other workbook / worksheet attributes are not copied - e.g.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] You also **cannot** copy worksheets between workbooks.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] You cannot copy a worksheet if the workbook is open in *read-only* or *write-only* mode.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] Now we know how to get a worksheet, we can start modifying cells content.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] This will return the cell at A4, or create one if it does not exist yet.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] There is also the `Worksheet.cell()` method.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] When a worksheet is created in memory, it contains no *cells*.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] Because of this feature, scrolling through cells instead of accessing them directly will create them all in memory, even if you don’t assign them a value.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] will create 100x100 cells in memory, for nothing.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] For performance reasons the `Worksheet.iter_cols()` method is not available in read-only mode.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] For performance reasons the `Worksheet.columns` property is not available in read-only mode.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] If you just want the values from a worksheet you can use the `Worksheet.values` property.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] This operation will overwrite existing files without warning.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] The filename extension is not forced to be xlsx or xlsm, although you might have some trouble opening it directly with another application if you don’t use an official extension.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] As OOXML files are basically ZIP files, you can also open it with your favourite ZIP archive manager.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] You should monitor the data attributes and document extensions for saving documents in the document templates and vice versa, otherwise the result table engine can not open the document.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] There are several flags that can be used in load_workbook.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] openpyxl does currently not read all possible items in an Excel file so shapes will be lost from existing files if they are opened and saved with the same name.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] Sometimes openpyxl will fail to open a workbook.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] This is usually because there is something wrong with the file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] If this is the case then openpyxl will try and provide some more information.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] Openpyxl follows the OOXML specification closely and will reject files that do not because they are invalid.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] When this happens you can use the exception from openpyxl to inform the developers of whichever application or library produced the file.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] As the OOXML specification is publicly available it is important that developers follow it.
[src:openpyxl-excel/tutorial] You can find the spec by searching for ECMA-376, most of the implementation specifics are in Part 4.
